1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,570
More and more leading universities are offering advanced management training programs for senior business executives.

2
00:00:07,840 --> 00:00:18,771
According to the sponsors, the big benefit of these programs is not that the executives get ready-made formulae that they can use to operate their business more efficiently.

3
00:00:19,040 --> 00:00:24,931
Rather, they benefit most from the opportunity to exchange and discuss new ideas.

4
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:33,331
Many of these programs require the executives to live together in college dormitories, thus encouraging bull sessions.

5
00:00:33,680 --> 00:00:39,971
Boiled down to one word, the executives benefit most from the stimulation received.

6
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:46,690
A year ago, I directed two sessions in a one-week sales management school in Atlanta,

7
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:50,531
sponsored by the National Sales Executives Incorporated.

8
00:00:50,800 --> 00:00:57,331
A few weeks later, I met a salesman friend who worked for one of the sales executives who'd attended the school.

9
00:00:57,840 --> 00:01:03,731
You people at the school sure gave my sales manager a lot of things to do to run our company better,

10
00:01:03,840 --> 00:01:05,170
my young friend said.

11
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:09,971
Curious, I asked him specifically what changes he'd noticed.

12
00:01:10,160 --> 00:01:14,690
He reeled off a number of things, a revision in the compensation plan,

13
00:01:14,800 --> 00:01:20,451
sales meetings twice a month instead of once a month, new business cards and stationery,

14
00:01:20,560 --> 00:01:26,851
a revision in sales territories, not one of which was specifically recommended in the training program.

15
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:30,610
The sales manager didn't get a bunch of canned techniques.

16
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:40,371
Instead, he got something much more valuable, the stimulation to think of ideas directly beneficial to his own particular organization.

17
00:01:41,201 --> 00:01:49,650
A young accountant for a paint manufacturer told me about a very successful venture of his that was sparked by the ideas of others.

18
00:01:50,160 --> 00:01:54,931
I never had had more than a casual interest in real estate, he told me.

19
00:01:55,120 --> 00:02:01,170
I've been a professional accountant for several years now, and I've stuck pretty close to my profession.

20
00:02:01,360 --> 00:02:08,371
One day a realtor friend invited me to be his guest at a luncheon of one of the city's real estate groups.

21
00:02:08,640 --> 00:02:12,690
The speaker that day was an older man who had seen the city grow.

22
00:02:12,880 --> 00:02:16,050
His talk was about the next twenty years.

23
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:22,931
He predicted that the metropolitan area would continue to grow far out into the surrounding farmland.

24
00:02:23,201 --> 00:02:29,090
He also predicted that there would be a record demand for what he called gentleman-size farms,

25
00:02:29,201 --> 00:02:35,411
two to five acres, big enough so the businessman or professional person could have a pool,

26
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:39,570
horses, a garden, and other hobbies that require space.

27
00:02:40,241 --> 00:02:42,931
This man's talk really stimulated me.

28
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:46,371
What he described was exactly what I wanted.

29
00:02:46,480 --> 00:02:53,971
The next few days I asked several friends what they thought about the idea of someday owning a five-acre estate.

